is purely for educational purposes and is not ready for production. Developers must carry out their own due diligence when it comes to deployment of smart contracts in production, including but not limited to, thorough audits, secure design practices, etc.A public FairyPort Relayer, one per chain, is ran that communicates with this contract typically. Projects can run their own FairyPort instance and own deployments of a Gateway contract at their discretion. TODO: HASH - create a github issue to add an extension for Gateway contracts where people can inherit this base contract and have callbacks to a specific contract (say it's a DEX dApp and it would benefit from having automatic callback upon decryption key generation). NOTE: Tx Sequence #1: BlockHeight Based FIDs --> FPort: submitEncryptionKey() & submitDecryptionKey(), where both update bytes vars `latestEncryptionKey`, and mapping `decryptionKeys[height]` are updated. I guess for any tx, if it's based on block height (which acts as the FID) it will have the same decryption key across the board. NOTE: Tx Sequence #2: General IDs : `requestGeneralID()` populating addressGeneralID[_msgSender()] for later. User then calls `requestGeneralDecryptionKey()` where event emitted RequestGeneralKey(_msgSender(), id). FairyPort listens for this. THEN, FairyPort calls `submitGeneralDecryptionKeys(requester, id, decryption key))` where the mapping generalDecryptionKeys[requester][id] is populated. Contracts can then query this for the DecryptionKey for them as the requester. NOTE: SO the key to this contract is that there are IDs (not FIDs) linked to the resultant decryption key mappings. These decryption key mappings differ based on the type of FIDs ultimately used (block-height based, or general). renounceOwnership().details: Leaves the contract without owner. It will not be possible to call `onlyOwner` functions. Can only be called by the current owner.
